Since commit_inputs is never set to true here when yes is true, are
damon_lru_sort_handle_commit_inputs() and the existing polling logic now
dead code?

The legacy background handler damon_lru_sort_handle_commit_inputs() checks
if (!commit_inputs) and will always return 0.

> +
> +	err = damon_call(ctx, &control);

Can passing damon_lru_sort.commit_inputs=Y as a kernel boot parameter cause
a NULL pointer dereference here?

During early boot, module_param_cb() parses the command line and invokes
this store function before the module initialization function runs. This
means the global ctx pointer will still be NULL when damon_call() is
invoked.

Should this include a check for damon_initialized() similar to the
enabled_store() callback?

If the module is currently disabled (enabled=N), does writing Y to
commit_inputs return -EINVAL?

When the context is not running, damon_call() will return -EINVAL. This
might unexpectedly fail for users who are legitimately trying to configure
and commit parameters prior to enabling the module, misleading them into
thinking their parameters are invalid.

